	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Perspectives on the state of EPA negotiations</h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 July 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>At an African Union (AU) EPA coordination meeting in May 2012, representatives of the AU described the EC’s market access regulation (MAR) proposals of September 2011 as ‘an attempt to force Africa into concluding negotiations at all cost[s]’. Representatives of Tanzania, the hosting government, highlighted the ‘the need to finalize negotiations at regional and WTO level before concluding EPA negotiations’ and the importance of putting content issues ‘such as supply-side constraints and policy space on top of the agenda rather than time frames’. Each region presented its perspectives on the state of play in the EPA process.&nbsp;</p><p>The EAC presentation noted that ‘contentious issues remain largely unresolved’, including the EAC’s MFN clause, export taxes and non-execution clause, while a continued divergence on economic and development cooperation issues was also noted. Although agreement had been reached on negotiating trade in services and trade-related issues at a later stage, there was no clear agreement on what matters fell into this category. EAC representatives maintained that their main aim was ‘to obtain an EPA that supports regional integration and the development of the region’.&nbsp;</p><p>The SADC representative indicated that ‘progress has been made on the draft text on cumulation’, but unresolved issues which were common to other regions remained. Negotiations on administrative cooperation issues were still ongoing, as were discussions on a range of detailed issues from treatment of products excluded from tariff reduction processes, through rules of origin for fisheries products, to SACU’s market access offer.&nbsp;</p><p>The ESA representative indicated that the four agreements signed bilaterally were now under implementation, but highlighted ‘the need to continuously review positions taking into account the new emerging economic realities that did not exist when EPA negotiations were launched ten years ago’.&nbsp;</p><p>The ECOWAS presentation reported a ‘lack of progress in the negotiations at the technical level’, with a need ‘to pursue political level engagements to move the negotiations forward’. They argued that ‘the emphasis that the EC is placing on differentiation and graduation of countries has implications for regional and continental integration.’ While West Africa has ‘designed an Economic Partnership Agreement Development Program (EPADP) with an estimated cost of Euro 15 billion’, the region considered there to be a ‘need to engage other players in the EU in order to get the EC to show understanding and flexibility on the concerns of African countries in the EPA negotiations’.&nbsp;</p><p>The Central African representative stated that ‘progress on EPAs has been very slow’, which was ‘attributable to divergences in market access and development issues’.&nbsp;</p><p>During the meeting, the need for strong lobbying around the proposed modification of MAR no. 1528/2007 was stressed, along with the importance of safeguarding regional and continental interests.&nbsp;</p><p>Business representatives present emphasised the importance of:&nbsp;</p>
<ul>

<li>maintaining established market access benefits;&nbsp;</li>

<li>preserving the right to use export taxes as a development tool;&nbsp;</li>

<li>addressing the issue of EU agricultural subsidies;&nbsp;</li>

<li>developing intra-African trade;&nbsp;</li>

<li>securing support for EPA implementation;&nbsp;</li>

<li>ensuring far greater government consultation with the private sector.&nbsp;</li>

</ul>
<p>Addressing the ACP–EU Joint Parliamentary Assembly in Denmark on 29 May, EC Trade Commissioner Karel De Gucht highlighted:</p>
<ul>

<li>the importance of ‘locking in’ existing duty-free, quota-free access to EU markets, in view of the impact of uncertainty and the pending EU GSP reforms, which would involve ‘removing a large number of countries from the list of beneficiaries’;</li>

<li>the benefits of lowering tariffs in terms of improved integration into global value chains;</li>

<li>the economies-of-scale benefits derived from the ‘regional integration that EPAs can support’.&nbsp;</li>

</ul>
<p>The Commissioner acknowledged, however, that in the Pacific, Central Africa and East and Southern Africa ‘there is still a way to go’. He maintained that progress was being made in the EAC negotiations but with ‘more technical work’ needed, and that in West Africa the ‘political heavy-lifting’ will ‘soon need to start’ to resolve outstanding issues. He highlighted the importance for Ghana and Côte d’Ivoire of ‘making sure that trade preferences for bananas and cocoa paste are maintained, now that the EU’s Generalised System of Preferences – soon to be adopted – ceases to be an alternative’.&nbsp;</p><p>Trade Commissioner De Gucht maintained that while some progress had been made in the SADC negotiations, the situation remained ‘challenging’, but pointed out that all issues that needed to be discussed were now on the table. He said: ‘Europe is prepared to eliminate more tariffs than its counterpart but we still need a balanced result.’</p><p>The Commissioner described the EC September 2011 proposals to modify MAR no. 1528/2007 as being part of the process, maintaining that the regulation allowed ‘plenty of time before the measure enters into force: sufficient time to ratify and apply existing interim EPAs as well as to conclude on-going negotiations and put those EPAs into application.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>African Union, ‘EPA negotiations coordination meeting, 17-18 May 2012, Arusha Tanzania’, TI/TD/EPA/01, May 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/files/2012/05/Final-EPA-Report-Eng-May2012.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.tralac.org/files/2012/05/Final-EPA-Report-Eng-May2012.pdf</a>&nbsp;</p><p>EC, ‘Completing a partnership’, speech by EU Trade Commissioner to EU–ACP Parliamentary Assembly, SPEECH/12/397, 29 May 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=SPEECH/12/397&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=0&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en" target="_blank">http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=SPEECH/12/397&am...</a>&nbsp;</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The EC GSP proposal will reduce the number of countries benefiting from the scheme from 176 to about 80, by removing the list of beneficiary countries that have better or equivalent access under another scheme (e.g. an FTA or an EPA) and by graduating out countries classified by the World Bank as ‘upper middle income’ and ‘high income’.&nbsp;</p><p>As highlighted by the comments of Commissioner De Gucht on the subject of bananas and cocoa paste for Côte d’Ivoire and Ghana, the ongoing EPA has important implications for access for food and agricultural products (particularly value-added products) to the EU market, since the EU retains on average higher tariffs for food and agricultural products under other trade regimes than for non-agricultural products.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
